<font color="#FF0000">PTSD AND CHILDREN</font><br>
<tt>Sun May  4 22:00:24 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all:<br>
     I believe what the case here is the behavior exhibited by the parent can be picked up by the child.  I am a elementary school teacher and am trained in child behavior, not to the degree of a professional like a doctor, but enough training with personal experience.  Art is very correct, children are like baby animals, &quot;monkey see, monkey do.&quot;  If a Vet had experienced PTSD and exhibeted its symptoms, a child might pick up on the behavior and repeat it.  As a teacher, I've seen some incredible things (children wise) and others can vouch for the truth.<br>
     I am also the son of a Vietnam vet, who through much good fortune was surrounded by people who cared and has been<br>
able to deal with the things that happened over there over time.  There is still not a day that goes by that he doesn't think about, so Doc Spatz, vets never get over Vietnam, they just learn to put it in a new light or perspective and see it as a part of life (much of it takes time and plenty of talking it out with those that care).<br>
     As the son of a veteran, I picked up a lot of behaviors of my father, things he learned in Nam.  I am always on the lookout, always suspicious of the motives of leaders and others (not to the point of Paranoia, but in a healthy way).  This is something I learned from my father.  I also learned to be direct and fight hard, to finish something that some else started.  My dad tempered these behaviors in Nam and I picked them up even at a young age.  I can imagine some children have picked up worse behaviors.  I've had friends whose attitude on life was affected by a father that was a Nam vet.  So Doc Spatz I think it is possible-NOT cross generational PTSD, but a form of learned behavior from parents.  I do have so authority in child psychology, maybe not like you, but some none the less.  These vets, Doc Del and Art Varinelli have merit in their arguments.  That is my opinion.<br>
     In regards to PTSD, Doc Spatz, you know time doesn't matter.  A few weeks in the desert can even be worse than a year in the jungle.  PTSD is highly individual in its causes.  I voulunteer to help vets, and I have known a Desert Storm soldier, who had PTSD after seeing a man die in a battle.  So, lay off the Desert Storm soldier, God knows what crap he has seen.
